{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox park | name = DeSalvio Playground | alt_name = | photo = | photo_width = | photo_caption = | photo_alt = | map = | map_width = | map_caption = | map_alt = | label = | label_position = | relief = | mark = | coords = {{coord|40.721787|-73.996087|format=dms|display=inline, title}} | coords_ref = | type = | location = on the corner of [[Spring Street (Manhattan)|Spring Street]] and [[Mulberry Street (Manhattan)|Mulberry Street]] in [[NoLita]], in [[Manhattan, New York City]] | nearest_city = | area = | elevation = | created = | designer = | etymology = | operator = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_ref = | status = | awards = | open = | camp_sites = | hiking_trails = | other_info = | website = |child = |embedded = }}
'''DeSalvio Playground''' is a neighborhood park located on the corner of [[Spring Street (Manhattan)|Spring Street]] and [[Mulberry Street (Manhattan)|Mulberry Street]] in [[NoLita]], in [[Manhattan, New York City]].<ref name="google1">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CJ0t9io_j7AC&pg=PA283&dq=%22DeSalvio+Playground%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DGwRUdfiOKyM0QG_4YCoDg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22DeSalvio%20Playground%22&f=false |title=Eyewitness Travel Family Guide New York City |author=Dorling Kindersley |publisher= Penguin|year= 2012|accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name="google2">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p0cbpUilQAMC&pg=PT137&dq=%22DeSalvio+Playground%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DGwRUdfiOKyM0QG_4YCoDg&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg |title=Fodor's New York City 2013 |author=Fodor's |publisher= Random House|year= 2012|accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/M218/ |title=DeSalvio Playground: NYC Parks |publisher=Nycgovparks.org |date= |accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref>
The playground has modular play equipment that is red, white, and green (in honor of the [[Italian flag]]), built-in stone chess tables, a basketball half-court, and benches.<ref name="google1"/><ref name="google2"/><ref name="nycgovparks1">{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/M218/history |title=DeSalvio Playground Highlights: NYC Parks |publisher=Nycgovparks.org |date= |accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref>
==History== The park honors John DeSalvio (1881–1948) and his son [[Louis DeSalvio]] (1910–2004). John DeSalvio, a [[first-generation American]], served as district leader of the Second Assembly District (West), and was one of a few Italian-Americans in the [[Tammany Hall]] political organization. Louis DeSalvio served as [[New York State Assembly|Second District New York State Assemblyman]]. The [[City of New York]] acquired the property in 1954 and turned it over to the Parks department. The playground opened on December 15, 1955 as "John DeSalvio Park".<ref name="nycgovparks1"/>
The playground hosted the Citywide [[Bocce Ball]] Championships in 1996 and 1997.<ref name="nycgovparks1"/><ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/10/14/nyregion/forget-baseball-who-won-in-boccie.html |title=Forget Baseball, Who Won in Boccie? |publisher=New York Times |date=October 14, 1996 |accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=DAVID M. HERSZENHORN |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/20/nyregion/mayor-steps-up-campaign-as-messinger-presses-on.html |title=Mayor Steps Up Campaign As Messinger Presses On |publisher=New York Times |date=October 20, 1997 |accessdate=February 5, 2013}}</ref>
